               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Understanding Gravity</h3>In the previous text, we mentioned gravity when defining a planet, but we didn’t explain the concept in detail. This section expands on that idea.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>The Space-time</h4>For a long time, we understood space, where we move, and time, which records the sequence of events, as absolute and separate dimensions. As a result, we believed that time was the same for everyone, whether it was a person reading this text, someone traveling in a car, or even an astronaut on a journey to the Moon",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4da1237a-2d61-4f76-8707-dccc5d90bb48",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "08",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "This understanding began to change in <htdate0>, when Albert Einstein proposed that space and time are relative, depending on the observer's motion. Although this idea may seem strange at first, it is not noticeable in our daily lives because we move at relatively slow speeds. However, numerous experiments have confirmed the accuracy of this theory, allowing us to explain phenomena like Mercury's orbit",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4da1237a-2d61-4f76-8707-dccc5d90bb48",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "08",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1905",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "In <htdate0>, Einstein introduced a more comprehensive theory—the General Theory of Relativity—which resolved the issue of Mercury's orbit along with other cosmological mysteries. This theory presents two essential concepts for our study",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4da1237a-2d61-4f76-8707-dccc5d90bb48",
                     "text": "Britannica, T. Editors of Encyclopaedia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "08",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7eee4ba3-54ef-420e-a6b4-6e8b80decb7b",
                     "text": "Odenwald, Sten",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5d8aaf88-d206-4576-8587-e3dc7403d259",
                     "text": "Pontzen, Andrew and Whyntie, Tom",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "d4212894-96ca-4ab2-9458-24ff2a8c5024",
                     "text": "Pontzen, Andrew and Whyntie, Tom",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c632d8ab-7347-4df4-825f-d2bc6f5cbd0b",
                     "text": "Pontzen, Andrew and Whyntie, Tom",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1916",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ":"
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul><li>The universe can be described by a four-dimensional structure known as <b>space-time</b>, which combines the three spatial coordinates (height, width, and depth) with time, forming a continuous four-dimensional fabric.</li><li>In space-time, the presence of mass curves this structure; in other words, objects with mass distort space-time around them.</li></ul></p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<h4>The planet and space-time</h4>When a planet forms, it tends to acquire a spherical or near-spherical shape, like an ellipsoid. In doing so, it curves the space-time, as illustrated in this section’s figure. The effect of moving within this curved space-time is what we call gravity. John Wheeler famously explained it this way: \"Matter tells space-time how to curve, and space-time tells matter how to move\". A clear example of this phenomenon is our planet’s orbit around the Sun, caused by the curvature that the Sun’s mass creates in space-time",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "16797baa-f339-4753-8c5f-66dbfeae3abd",
                     "text": "Stannard, W. B.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
